            "question": "Identify the causal DAG among ['BirthAsphyxia', 'HypDistrib', 'HypoxiaInO2'] to model congenital heart disease in babies. Output a list of directed-edge tuples inside <Answer></Answer>.",
            "response_raw": "To analyze the causal relationships between the given variables related to congenital heart disease in babies, we can consider the following descriptions:\n\n1. **BirthAsphyxia**: This condition refers to a lack of oxygen to the blood during the infant's birth. It can lead to various complications, including hypoxia.\n2. **HypDistrib**: This refers to low oxygen areas that are equally distributed around the body. This condition can arise from various factors, including birth asphyxia.\n3. **HypoxiaInO2**: This condition describes hypoxia that occurs even when breathing oxygen. It can be a consequence of poor oxygen distribution in the body.\n\nBased on these descriptions, we can infer the following causal relationships:\n\n- **BirthAsphyxia** can lead to **HypDistrib** because a lack of oxygen during birth can cause uneven oxygen distribution in the body.\n- **HypDistrib** can lead to **HypoxiaInO2** because if there are low oxygen areas in the body, even breathing oxygen may not alleviate the hypoxia.\n\nThus, the directed edges in the causal graph would be:\n- From **BirthAsphyxia** to **HypDistrib**\n- From **HypDistrib** to **HypoxiaInO2**\n\nThere are no isolated nodes in this case, as all nodes are interconnected through causal relationships.\n\nThe final directed acyclic graph (DAG) representation is as follows:\n\n<Answer>[('BirthAsphyxia', 'HypDistrib'), ('HypDistrib', '",
